        <h1>GonoPBX meets Home Assistant</h1>
      </div>

      <div class="blog-article-content">

        <p>
          If you run a smart home with Home Assistant, you probably want to see
          <em>everything</em> in one dashboard: lights, heating, cameras – and why not your
          phone system too? Now you can.
        </p>

        <h2>What does the integration do?</h2>

        <p>
          The Home Assistant integration connects GonoPBX to your smart home via two channels:
          a <strong>REST API</strong> for sensors and actions, and <strong>MQTT</strong>
          for real-time events.
        </p>

        <h3>Sensors</h3>
        <p>
          GonoPBX exposes the following information as Home Assistant sensors:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Extensions</strong> – Online/offline status for each extension (binary sensor)</li>
          <li><strong>Trunks</strong> – Registration status of SIP lines</li>
          <li><strong>Active calls</strong> – Number of current calls</li>
          <li><strong>Calls today</strong> – Counter of calls for the current day</li>
          <li><strong>Voicemail</strong> – Number of unread voice messages</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>MQTT events</h3>
        <p>
          For every call, GonoPBX sends events over MQTT. This enables automations – for example:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Blink lights when the phone rings</li>
          <li>Mute the TV on incoming calls</li>
          <li>Push notification on missed calls</li>
          <li>Show caller info on a hallway display</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Click-to-call</h3>
        <p>
          Using the <strong>originate endpoint</strong>, you can start calls directly from
          Home Assistant. Your phone rings first, and once you pick up, the target number is dialed.
          Perfect for:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A “Call” button in the HA dashboard</li>
          <li>Automated calls on alarms (e.g., water sensor)</li>
          <li>Speed dial via a wall-mounted tablet</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Setup in 3 steps</h2>

        <h3>1. Configure MQTT broker</h3>
        <p>
          Under <strong>Settings → Home Assistant</strong> in the GonoPBX UI,
          configure the MQTT broker. Usually this is the IP of your Home Assistant instance
          with the Mosquitto add-on.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Generate API key</h3>
        <p>
          In the same section, generate an API key. This key is used in Home Assistant
          for authentication. Click “Generate key” and copy it.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Configure Home Assistant</h3>
        <p>
          In Home Assistant’s <code>configuration.yaml</code>, set up REST and MQTT sensors.
          A detailed guide with ready-to-use YAML snippets is available on the
          <a href="/en/homeassistant" style="color:#3182ce;font-weight:600;">integration page</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>Security</h2>

        <p>
          Communication is secured by two mechanisms:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>API key</strong> – Every REST request must send a valid key in the header</li>
          <li><strong>MQTT auth</strong> – The MQTT broker is accessed with username/password (Mosquitto standard)</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          The API key can be regenerated at any time in the GonoPBX UI if it is compromised.
        </p>

        <h2>Example automation</h2>

        <p>
          Here’s a simple example: blink the hallway lights on an incoming call.
        </p>

        <pre><code set:html={`automation:
  - alias: "Phone ringing - blink light"
    trigger:
      - platform: mqtt
        topic: "gonopbx/events/call"
    condition:
      - condition: template
        value_template: "{{ trigger.payload_json.event == 'ringing' }}"
    action:
      - service: light.turn_on
        target:
          entity_id: light.hallway
        data:
          flash: short`} /></pre>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
